{"key":"post-13994588","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13994588</id>\n<content>You can stack jars in a PC.&amp;nbsp; What will happen is that it will take much longer for steam to begin venting as you're warming it up.&amp;nbsp; It will also take longer to come up to pressure because you have so much more material to heat up.&amp;nbsp; However, once it's fully up to pressure, you can use the same time.&amp;nbsp; If it's BRF jars, use 1 hour.&amp;nbsp; If quart jars of grains, use 90 minutes, but you don't start the timer until 15 psi is reached.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It should go without saying that when using jars or spawn bags in a pressure cooker, steam should be able to permeate all the way around each substrate.&amp;nbsp; In other words, don't put two large spawn bags up against each other or one on top of the other without a spacer which allows steam to penetrate the gap between them.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>13994585</prev>\n<first>13993690</first>\n<last>13994588</last>\n<when>1298216728</when>\n<utime>02/20/11 05:45 PM</utime>\n</post>"}